# Web Penetration Tester Roadmap

This is a comprehensive roadmap to becoming a **Web Penetration Tester** for in-depth learning. This guide covers everything from foundational web technologies to advanced vulnerability analysis and certifications. Follow this roadmap step-by-step to specialize in web security.

## Timeline Overview

| Timeline         | Key Focus Areas                         |
| ---------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| **3-6 months**   | HTML/CSS/JavaScript, Web Architecture, HTTP Basics, Web Vulnerabilities |
| **6-12 months**  | Advanced Web Exploitation Techniques, Scripting for Automation, Tools like Burp Suite |
| **Ongoing**      | Practice on CTF platforms, Certifications, Staying updated on latest threats |

---

## 1. Master Web Fundamentals

### What to Learn
- **HTML/CSS**: Structure and design of websites
- **JavaScript**: Client-side scripting (focus on DOM manipulation, XSS)
- **Web Servers & Databases**: Apache, Nginx, MySQL, PostgreSQL
- **HTTP/HTTPS Protocols**: Status codes, methods (GET, POST), headers, sessions, cookies
- **Web Architectures**: Frontend, backend, and APIs

### Resources
- Free Course: [FreeCodeCamp HTML & CSS](https://www.freecodecamp.org/)
- Course: [JavaScript for Beginners](https://www.udemy.com/course/the-complete-javascript-course/)
- Book: [HTTP: The Definitive Guide](https://www.amazon.com/HTTP-Definitive-Guide-David-Gourley/dp/1565925092)

---

## 2. Understand Web Security Fundamentals

### What to Learn
- **Web Application Security Basics**: OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities
- **Common Vulnerabilities**:
  - **SQL Injection** (SQLi)
  - **Cross-Site Scripting** (XSS)
  - **Cross-Site Request Forgery** (CSRF)
  - **Command Injection**
  - **Directory Traversal**
  - **Insecure Deserialization**
  - **Security Misconfiguration**
- **Authentication Mechanisms**: OAuth, JWT, session management

### Tools
- **Burp Suite**: For web application scanning and manual testing
- **OWASP ZAP**: Open-source security scanner

### Resources
- **OWASP Top 10**: [OWASP Official Site](https://owasp.org/Top10/)
- Web Hacking Course: [PortSwigger Academy](https://portswigger.net/web-security)
- Book: [The Web Application Hackerâ€™s Handbook](https://www.amazon.com/Web-Application-Hackers-Handbook-Exploiting/dp/1118026470/) by Dafydd Stuttard

---

## 3. Learn Web Exploitation Techniques

### What to Learn
- **SQL Injection (SQLi)**: Blind, Union-based, Time-based SQLi
- **Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)**: Stored, Reflected, DOM-based XSS
- **Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)**: Understanding token-based security
- **File Inclusion Vulnerabilities**: Local File Inclusion (LFI), Remote File Inclusion (RFI)
- **Authentication and Session Hijacking**: Password cracking, session fixation
- **Business Logic Flaws**: Authorization issues, workflow manipulation
- **API Vulnerabilities**: REST, GraphQL, OAuth security weaknesses

### Tools
- **SQLMap**: Automate SQL injection detection and exploitation
- **XSS Hunter**: Platform for finding and exploiting XSS vulnerabilities
- **Nmap & Nikto**: Scanning tools to map and discover web vulnerabilities

### Resources
- Book: [Web Hacking 101](https://leanpub.com/web-hacking-101) by Peter Yaworski
- Free Course: [Web Security Academy](https://portswigger.net/web-security)
- Hands-on labs: [TryHackMe](https://tryhackme.com/), [Hack The Box](https://www.hackthebox.com/)

---

## 4. Master Tools of the Trade

### What to Learn
- **Burp Suite**: In-depth understanding of using Burp for proxying, scanning, and exploiting vulnerabilities manually
- **OWASP ZAP**: Automating scanning for vulnerabilities
- **Postman/Insomnia**: For testing and exploiting APIs
- **Browser Dev Tools**: Useful for client-side attacks and debugging
- **Tamper Data**: Intercepting and modifying HTTP requests

### Resources
- Course: [Burp Suite Pro - Web Application Security](https://www.udemy.com/course/burp-suite/)
- OWASP ZAP Documentation: [OWASP ZAP Official Documentation](https://www.zaproxy.org/docs/)
- Tool Practice: [Vulnhub](https://www.vulnhub.com/), [Damn Vulnerable Web App (DVWA)](http://www.dvwa.co.uk/)

---

## 5. Learn Scripting and Automation

### What to Learn
- **Python**: For writing custom scripts for automation and vulnerability testing
- **Bash**: For automating repetitive tasks
- **JavaScript**: For exploiting client-side vulnerabilities (XSS)
- **PowerShell**: For Windows-based exploitation

### Tools to Create
- Custom payload generators
- Automated vulnerability scanning tools
- Web scraping for data extraction

### Resources
- [Learn Python the Hard Way](https://learnpythonthehardway.org/)
- [Violent Python](https://www.amazon.com/Violent-Python-Cookbook-Penetration-Engineers/dp/1597499579)
- Hands-on: [Hack The Box Python Challenges](https://www.hackthebox.com/)

---

## 6. Deep Dive into API Security

### What to Learn
- **REST and GraphQL API security**: Authentication, session management, and rate-limiting
- **API Exploits**: Parameter tampering, mass assignment, security misconfigurations
- **OAuth/OpenID**: Security flows and token vulnerabilities

### Tools
- **Postman**: API testing and exploring vulnerabilities
- **Insomnia**: API vulnerability hunting
- **JWT.io**: For decoding, verifying, and tampering JWT tokens

### Resources
- [API Security Top 10](https://apisecurity.io/)
- Book: [API Security in Action](https://www.amazon.com/API-Security-Action-Neil-Madden/dp/1617296021) by Neil Madden
- API Labs: [Portswigger API Academy](https://portswigger.net/web-security/api)

---

## 7. Gain Hands-On Experience with CTF Platforms

### What to Do
- Regular practice on **Capture The Flag (CTF)** platforms to refine your web exploitation skills.
- Participate in **Bug Bounties** to gain real-world experience by finding vulnerabilities in live systems.

### CTF Resources
- **Hack The Box**: [HackTheBox.com](https://www.hackthebox.com)
- **TryHackMe**: [TryHackMe.com](https://tryhackme.com)
- **OverTheWire**: [OverTheWire.org](https://overthewire.org/)
- **Bug Bounty**: [HackerOne](https://www.hackerone.com/), [Bugcrowd](https://www.bugcrowd.com/)

---

## 8. Stay Updated & Join the Community

### What to Do
- Cybersecurity is dynamic and continuously evolving. Follow blogs, attend conferences, and join online security communities to stay updated on new threats and techniques.

### Resources
- **Blogs**: [Krebs on Security](https://krebsonsecurity.com/), [Hacker News](https://thehackernews.com/)
- **Conferences**: DEF CON, Black Hat, OWASP AppSec
- **Communities**: Reddit r/netsec, Twitter, Slack channels, Discord servers

---

## 9. Obtain Certifications

### Certifications to Pursue
- **Certified Ethical Hacker (CEH)**: Entry-level certification for ethical hacking
- **Offensive Security Web Expert (OSWE)**: Advanced certification focusing on web application exploitation
- **Bug Bounty Hunter**: Self-taught, real-world recognition through bug bounties

### Resources
- **CEH**: [Certified Ethical Hacker Official Guide](https://www.eccouncil.org/programs/certified-ethical-hacker-ceh/)
- **OSWE**: [Offensive Security Web Expert Guide](https://www.offensive-security.com/courses-and-certifications/oswe/)
- **HackerOne/Bugcrowd**: Platforms to practice web exploitation in real-world scenarios

---

## Suggested Roadmap Timeline
- **3-6 months**: Web basics (HTML, CSS, JavaScript), web security fundamentals, HTTP protocol, OWASP Top 10
- **6-12 months**: Web exploitation techniques, Burp Suite, scripting (Python/Bash), API security
- **Ongoing**: Hands-on practice on CTF platforms, bug bounties, certifications
